1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,500
Get off my sight, Frank. You are fired, and you are
not getting a single dime of your $2 million bonus.

2
00:00:06,260 --> 00:00:08,660
The CEO smirked, thinking he had won.

3
00:00:09,180 --> 00:00:11,980
He did not know that my next phone
call would cost him $40 million.

4
00:00:12,860 --> 00:00:13,820
Rewind three months.

5
00:00:14,280 --> 00:00:16,960
I have spent 32 years in
commercial contracting.

6
00:00:17,720 --> 00:00:22,540
In this industry, you do not survive by sitting
in a carpeted office looking at stock options.

7
00:00:22,540 --> 00:00:28,340
You survive by understanding the chemistry of
concrete pores, the tolerances of structural steel,

9
00:00:31,180 --> 00:00:31,940
and the strict codes of
municipal inspectors.

10
00:00:35,160 --> 00:00:35,920
For 22 of those years, I worked
for Caldwell Construction, LLC.

11
00:00:37,940 --> 00:00:38,520
The company was founded
by Richard Caldwell.

12
00:00:43,280 --> 00:00:47,840
Richard was an old school builder who started with a single backhoe in the
late 1970s. He built a $50 million a year firm based on two simple principles.

13
00:00:48,420 --> 00:00:52,380
You pay your subcontractors on time,
and you never cut corners on quality.

14
00:00:53,060 --> 00:00:57,300
Richard knew I was the operational engine
that kept his biggest projects running.

16
00:01:02,480 --> 00:01:09,200
Five years ago, when we bid on the Oak Creek Municipal School District High School campus
expansion, a massive $40 million public works contract under California jurisdiction, Richard

17
00:01:09,200 --> 00:01:14,280
knew it would take every ounce of my experience to
pull it off. It was an incredibly complex project.

18
00:01:15,160 --> 00:01:20,040
We were building a new three-story science and
technology wing, a state-of-the-art gymnasium,

19
00:01:20,320 --> 00:01:25,680
and updating the entire utility infrastructure for
a campus built in the 1950s, all while keeping

20
00:01:25,680 --> 00:01:32,060
the school operational for 3,000 students. In
public works, the margin for error is razor thin.

21
00:01:32,500 --> 00:01:37,320
If you miss a deadline, the liquidated damages
clauses will eat your profit margin alive.

22
00:01:38,220 --> 00:01:43,960
If you fail a foundation inspection, you can end
up tearing out $100,000 worth of structural slab.

23
00:01:44,460 --> 00:01:49,660
To ensure I stayed focused on this project until the
very end, Richard and I signed a project-specific

24
00:01:49,660 --> 00:01:55,560
rider to my employment contract. It was a legally
drafted agreement. In addition to my base salary,

25
00:01:55,680 --> 00:02:01,720
I was entitled to a 5% project completion
bonus, based on the total contract value.

26
00:02:01,720 --> 00:02:03,540
That was $2 million.

27
00:02:03,540 --> 00:02:05,100
The conditions were simple.

28
00:02:05,100 --> 00:02:09,900
The project had to hit substantial completion
under budget, on time, and without outstanding

29
00:02:09,900 --> 00:02:12,680
subcontractor liens.

30
00:02:12,680 --> 00:02:17,080
Substantial completion in commercial
contracting is a legally defined milestone.

31
00:02:17,080 --> 00:02:21,780
It means the building is safe to occupy, the
school district can move their furniture in,

32
00:02:21,780 --> 00:02:25,660
and the local building department issues
the temporary certificate of occupancy.

33
00:02:25,660 --> 00:02:30,360
It is verified only when the lead
architect signs off on AIA document G704.

34
00:02:30,740 --> 00:02:33,160
For four years, I lived
and breathed Oak Creek.

35
00:02:33,680 --> 00:02:35,140
I worked 60-hour weeks.

36
00:02:35,580 --> 00:02:37,840
I managed 65 subcontractors.

37
00:02:37,840 --> 00:02:43,080
I negotiated directly with utility companies,
resolved conflicts with structural engineers,

38
00:02:43,400 --> 00:02:45,320
and kept our safety records spotless.

39
00:02:45,960 --> 00:02:49,280
By the time we hit the home
stretch, we were 96% complete.

40
00:02:49,700 --> 00:02:54,440
We were two months ahead of schedule, and
we were running $1.5 million under budget.

42
00:02:57,600 --> 00:02:58,500
My $2 million bonus was
my retirement ticket.

43
00:03:04,060 --> 00:03:04,640
I was 52, my knees were starting to fail from
decades on concrete slabs, and this was my exit.

44
00:03:06,580 --> 00:03:07,040
Then Richard Caldwell suffered a stroke.

45
00:03:10,480 --> 00:03:11,240
He survived, but his doctors
ordered him to retire immediately.

46
00:03:14,720 --> 00:03:15,380
Richard's wife convinced him to hand
over the reins of Caldwell Construction.

47
00:03:20,860 --> 00:03:21,400
Since Richard's own kids had gone into medicine and
law, the leadership fell to his nephew, Ryan Caldwell.

48
00:03:21,420 --> 00:03:22,260
Ryan was 32.

49
00:03:22,780 --> 00:03:26,220
He had an undergraduate degree in
communications and an Ivy League MBA.

50
00:03:26,740 --> 00:03:28,540
He had never held a hammer in his life.

51
00:03:29,080 --> 00:03:31,740
The closest Ryan had ever
come to a construction site

52
00:03:31,740 --> 00:03:34,940
was looking at drone footage
from a heated corporate office.

53
00:03:35,780 --> 00:03:38,760
He viewed the business not as a
craft of building brick and mortar,

54
00:03:38,760 --> 00:03:43,260
but as a series of spreadsheets where
expenses were just numbers to be minimized.

55
00:03:43,700 --> 00:03:45,120
Within two weeks of taking over,

56
00:03:45,600 --> 00:03:48,800
Ryan hired Brad Vance as the
new chief financial officer.

57
00:03:49,520 --> 00:03:54,140
Brad was a 40-year-old corporate accountant who
had spent his career at mid-size tax firms,

58
00:03:54,620 --> 00:03:59,120
finding loopholes to avoid paying overtime
and delaying payments to vendors to inflate

59
00:03:59,120 --> 00:04:05,060
corporate cash reserves. The day Brad arrived on
site, he walked into my project trailer wearing

60
00:04:05,060 --> 00:04:10,800
a $3,000 suit and pristine leather shoes that
had never touched gravel. He looked at my layout

61
00:04:10,800 --> 00:04:15,240
tables, my submittal logs, and the stack
of approved subcontractor invoices.

62
00:04:15,940 --> 00:04:18,720
Frank, Brad said, leaning against my desk.

63
00:04:19,220 --> 00:04:21,780
We have been reviewing the
project financials for Oak Creek.

64
00:04:22,420 --> 00:04:24,800
Ryan and I think the operating
expenses are too high.

65
00:04:25,220 --> 00:04:27,880
We need to optimize our cash
flow before the quarter ends.

66
00:04:28,420 --> 00:04:30,940
The project is under
budget, Brad, I replied.

67
00:04:31,420 --> 00:04:33,360
Not looking up from my
structural drawings.

68
00:04:33,940 --> 00:04:36,320
We are saving the company 1.5 million.

69
00:04:36,820 --> 00:04:40,160
The sub-correctors are working hard
because they know we pay them net 30.

70
00:04:40,700 --> 00:04:43,660
We do not touch the operating
budget, Brad smiled.

71
00:04:43,660 --> 00:04:45,880
It was a cold, calculated smile.

72
00:04:46,380 --> 00:04:49,320
We are going to adjust the payment
cycles for the subcontractors.

73
00:04:49,800 --> 00:04:52,820
Instead of net 30, we are
moving everyone to net 90.

74
00:04:53,620 --> 00:04:56,660
That keeps more cash in our
accounts for the quarterly report.

75
00:04:57,200 --> 00:04:59,540
You cannot do that, I
said, putting my pen down.

76
00:05:00,240 --> 00:05:02,080
These are public works subcontractors.

77
00:05:02,500 --> 00:05:04,380
They have payroll to meet every Friday.

78
00:05:05,180 --> 00:05:07,740
If you hold their money for 90
days, they will stop delivery.

79
00:05:08,140 --> 00:05:09,780
The structural steel fabricator.

80
00:05:10,100 --> 00:05:11,420
The mechanical contractor.

81
00:05:11,420 --> 00:05:14,540
They only work with us because
they trust our payment schedule.

82
00:05:15,460 --> 00:05:17,580
You delay them, and this site goes cold.

83
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:24,020
We will miss the completion deadline, and the school district
will hit us with $10,000 a day in liquidated damages.

84
00:05:24,720 --> 00:05:26,100
Ryan is the CEO now.

85
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:27,720
Frank, Brad said softly.

86
00:05:28,340 --> 00:05:30,400
We manage the money, you
just build the walls.

87
00:05:31,340 --> 00:05:36,740
Over the next two months, the atmosphere on the Oak Creek
site shifted from a cooperative build to an active war zone.

89
00:05:41,580 --> 00:05:42,140
Brad Vance began systematically delaying
payments to our core subcontractors.

90
00:05:45,960 --> 00:05:46,300
The mechanical sub, a local family-owned
outfit called Miller & Sons HVAC,

91
00:05:47,900 --> 00:05:48,380
was the first to sound the alarm.

92
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:50,480
They had 40 technicians on site,

93
00:05:54,980 --> 00:05:58,720
installing the complex variable refrigerant flow systems for the new science
labs. The owner, Tom Miller, walked into my trailer one Tuesday morning,

94
00:05:59,340 --> 00:06:03,080
holding a printout of an
unpaid invoice for $350,000.

95
00:06:03,820 --> 00:06:06,320
Frank, what is going on
at your corporate office?

96
00:06:06,740 --> 00:06:12,400
Tom asked, throwing the paper on my table. We
are 60 days out on our progress billing for the

97
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:17,380
third floor ductwork. My bank is refusing to
extend our line of credit. If I do not get paid

98
00:06:17,380 --> 00:06:22,600
by Friday, I cannot meet payroll. I will have to
pull my guys. I signed off on your pay app weeks

99
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:28,960
ago, Tom, I said, checking my log. It was sent to
accounting on the 5th. I will call Brad. I called

100
00:06:28,960 --> 00:06:34,940
Brad's direct line. It went to voicemail. I called
Ryan's office. His administrative assistant told

101
00:06:34,940 --> 00:06:39,360
me he was in a board meeting and cannot be
disturbed. I knew what they were doing. They

102
00:06:39,360 --> 00:06:44,960
were hoarding cash to show artificial liquidity
on their mid-year balance sheet. I spent the next

103
00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:49,780
three days calling every contact I had in the
industry, begging the subcontractors to stay on

104
00:06:49,780 --> 00:06:55,700
site. I promised them I would get it sorted out.
They trusted me. Many of these owners had worked

105
00:06:55,700 --> 00:07:02,300
with me for 20 years. They stayed, but the tension
was thick. By the time we hit 96% completion,

106
00:07:02,300 --> 00:07:07,440
we were preparing for the final inspections. The
school district was already scheduling their

107
00:07:07,440 --> 00:07:12,840
moving trucks. This was the moment my contract
writer specified. The final push toward the

108
00:07:12,840 --> 00:07:18,200
certificate of occupancy. If we crossed
the line, my $2 million bonus would vest,

109
00:07:18,720 --> 00:07:22,920
and Caldwell Construction would be legally
obligated to pay it within 30 days of the

110
00:07:22,920 --> 00:07:29,340
architect's signature on the G704 form. On a
rainy Thursday afternoon, I received an email

111
00:07:29,340 --> 00:07:34,860
from Ryan's assistant. It was a formal request
for a meeting in the main project trailer at 4.30

112
00:07:34,860 --> 00:07:40,820
p.m. The topic was listed as Project Closeout and
Audit Review. When I walked into the conference

113
00:07:40,820 --> 00:07:46,740
room, Ryan was sitting at the head of the table.
He had a new iPad in front of him. Brad Vance sat

114
00:07:46,740 --> 00:07:51,840
to his right next to a stack of manila folders.
Two men in dark suits I had never seen before

115
00:07:51,840 --> 00:07:57,420
were standing near the door. They were private
security. Have a seat, Frank, Ryan said, gesturing

116
00:07:57,420 --> 00:08:02,540
to the chair opposite him. His voice had a
rehearsed formal tone. What is going on, Ryan?

117
00:08:02,840 --> 00:08:08,100
I asked, sitting down. We have the fire marshal,
coming tomorrow at 8 a.m. for the final alarm

118
00:08:08,100 --> 00:08:12,940
system test. I need to be out there with the
electrical foreman. We have been performing an

119
00:08:12,940 --> 00:08:19,080
internal audit of the Oak Creek project accounts.
Frank, Brad Vance said, opening one of the folders,

120
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:24,240
specifically the change orders approved over
the last six months. We have found some very

121
00:08:24,240 --> 00:08:29,700
disturbing discrepancies. He slid a document across
the table. It was a change order authorization

122
00:08:29,700 --> 00:08:36,140
for the high school science lab HVIC systems,
an additional $450,000 for high-capacity

123
00:08:36,140 --> 00:08:41,300
particulate filters that the school district had
requested after a change in state building codes.

124
00:08:41,880 --> 00:08:48,260
This change order was signed by you, Frank, Ryan
said, his eyes narrowing. You authorized the

125
00:08:48,260 --> 00:08:53,500
subcontractor to purchase and install this
equipment, but we have checked our server logs

126
00:08:53,500 --> 00:08:58,520
and the project database. There is no record of
the school board ever approving this change.

127
00:08:58,900 --> 00:09:01,980
There is no signed authorization
from the district's representative.

128
00:09:02,760 --> 00:09:07,960
I stared at the document. What are you talking
about? The school board approved this in their

129
00:09:07,960 --> 00:09:13,080
public session on March 12th. I received the signed
