130
00:09:13,300 --> 00:09:19,180
Dr. Marcus, via email on March 14th. I uploaded
it to our Procore system and cc'd both of you.

131
00:09:19,180 --> 00:09:24,680
We checked Procore Frank, Brad said, his
face completely flat. There is no such file.

132
00:09:25,200 --> 00:09:30,440
We also reviewed your corporate email account.
There are no emails from Dr. Marcus on or around

133
00:09:30,440 --> 00:09:35,560
that date. It appears you authorized a
half-million-dollar expense to a subcontractor

134
00:09:35,560 --> 00:09:41,020
without owner approval. That is a direct violation
of company policy and constitutes gross financial

135
00:09:41,020 --> 00:09:47,560
negligence. I felt a cold sensation in my chest. I
realized instantly what had happened. Brad Vance

136
00:09:47,560 --> 00:09:52,580
had administrative access to our IT infrastructure.
He had deleted the files from the Procore server

137
00:09:52,580 --> 00:09:57,600
and wiped the emails from my inbox. They had
spent the last week erasing the digital trail.

138
00:09:58,320 --> 00:10:03,260
This is a setup, I said, looking Ryan dead
in the eye. You know Dr. Marcus signed that

139
00:10:03,260 --> 00:10:08,500
authorization. The school district's own records
will prove it. All you have to do is call their

140
00:10:08,500 --> 00:10:14,720
procurement office. We do not need to call anyone,
Frank, Ryan said, leaning back. The internal

141
00:10:14,720 --> 00:10:20,960
records of Caldwell Construction are what matter.
You expose this company to a $450,000 liability.

142
00:10:21,780 --> 00:10:27,060
Under Section 9 of your contract, gross negligence
is grounds for immediate termination for cause.

143
00:10:27,580 --> 00:10:33,060
Brad slid another paper toward me. This is your
termination letter, effective immediately.

144
00:10:33,680 --> 00:10:38,480
Because you are being terminated for cause,
your project completion bonus is forfeited.

145
00:10:38,760 --> 00:10:43,880
Your health insurance will terminate at midnight,
and you are barred from entering any Caldwell

146
00:10:43,880 --> 00:10:49,580
construction property. The two men by the door
stepped forward. These gentlemen will escort you

147
00:10:49,580 --> 00:10:54,720
to your desk to collect your personal items,
Ryan said. Your company truck has already been

148
00:10:54,720 --> 00:11:00,080
deactivated. We have arranged for a rideshare
to take you home. They expected me to blow up.

149
00:11:00,580 --> 00:11:06,340
They expected me to scream, throw chairs, and
threaten to sue. But I have spent 30 years

150
00:11:06,340 --> 00:11:10,860
dealing with corrupt developers and shady
inspectors. I have learned that when your

151
00:11:10,860 --> 00:11:15,280
opponent thinks they have you cornered, the best
thing you can do is let them think they have won.

152
00:11:15,780 --> 00:11:21,460
If I argued, they would use my anger as further
justification. If I refused to leave, they would

153
00:11:21,460 --> 00:11:26,760
have the police arrest me for trespassing, which
would destroy my credibility. I looked at Ryan.

154
00:11:27,140 --> 00:11:31,820
He was trying to look tough, but I could see the
slight tremor in his hand. He was terrified of me.

155
00:11:32,080 --> 00:11:37,700
He knew he was stealing my life savings. Okay, I
said. I stood up, adjusted my hard hat, and looked

156
00:11:37,700 --> 00:11:43,000
at Brad. You think you are smart, Brad. You think
because you can delete an email, you have cleaned

157
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:48,860
up the mess. We have the data, Frank, Brad said.
No, I replied. You have the files you control.

158
00:11:49,300 --> 00:11:54,160
But you do not control the people on this site.
And you definitely do not control the laws of

159
00:11:54,160 --> 00:11:59,240
this state. I walked out of the conference room.
The security guards followed me to my trailer.

160
00:11:59,840 --> 00:12:04,620
I packed my personal notebook, my old
leather-bound daily log, and my personal safety

161
00:12:04,620 --> 00:12:10,480
harness into a cardboard box. I handed over my
keys and my company-issued phone. Ten minutes

162
00:12:10,480 --> 00:12:15,780
later, I was standing in the rain outside the
construction gates, holding my box. The security

163
00:12:15,780 --> 00:12:21,460
guards locked the chain-link fence behind me. I
got into the rideshare they ordered. As we drove

164
00:12:21,460 --> 00:12:27,480
away, I looked back at the massive steel frame of
the high school expansion. Ryan and Brad thought

165
00:12:27,480 --> 00:12:31,760
they had just saved two million dollars. What
they did not know was that they had just pulled

166
00:12:31,760 --> 00:12:37,000
the pin on a grenade, and they were sitting on
the lever. When I got home, I did not waste time

167
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:42,560
feeling sorry for myself. I sat down at my kitchen
table, poured a glass of water, and booted up my

168
00:12:42,560 --> 00:12:48,820
personal laptop. I plugged in my encrypted external
hard drive. For 22 years, I had maintained

169
00:12:48,820 --> 00:12:54,480
a simple rule. Never trust a corporate server.
Every contract, every change order, every email

170
00:12:54,480 --> 00:12:59,800
exchange, and every progress payment application
I touched was backed up locally. It was not

171
00:12:59,800 --> 00:13:04,780
corporate espionage. It was basic professional
self-defense. I opened the folder labeled Oak

172
00:13:04,780 --> 00:13:10,340
Creek High School Expansion. In a subfolder named
Change Orders, I found the file, Science Lab HVAC

173
00:13:10,340 --> 00:13:16,320
Upgrades. It was a digital PDF, signed and stamped
by the school district superintendent, Dr. Marcus,

174
00:13:16,480 --> 00:13:21,600
and the lead architect. The file metadata was
intact, showing it was uploaded to Procore months

175
00:13:21,600 --> 00:13:27,760
ago and CC'd to both Ryan Caldwell and Brad Vance.
That was my shield against their claim of gross

176
00:13:27,760 --> 00:13:32,820
negligence, then I opened the folder named
Subcontractor Ledger. Here was the weapon.

177
00:13:33,600 --> 00:13:40,160
Under California Civil Code sections 8132 to 8138,
to receive monthly progress payments from a public

178
00:13:40,160 --> 00:13:46,240
owner, a general contractor must submit signed
unconditional lien waivers and releases from its

179
00:13:46,240 --> 00:13:52,440
subcontractors. These waivers legally declare that
the subcontractors have been paid in full for the

180
00:13:52,440 --> 00:13:57,340
work performed during the billing cycle. If
a contractor submits false waivers to obtain

181
00:13:57,340 --> 00:14:03,520
public funds, it constitutes a felony under
California Penal Code Section 115. I compared

182
00:14:03,520 --> 00:14:08,660
the pay applications Brad Vance had submitted to
the Oak Creek School District with my own records.

183
00:14:09,360 --> 00:14:14,240
Two weeks before my termination, Brad had
submitted pay application 18 to draw down

184
00:14:14,240 --> 00:14:20,300
$6 million in public funds. Attached to that
draw request were unconditional lien waivers,

185
00:14:20,720 --> 00:14:25,600
bearing the signatures of the executives from
Miller & Sons HVAC, Apex Structural Steel and

186
00:14:25,600 --> 00:14:30,640
Valley Concrete. According to those documents,
they had been paid. But my local files held the

187
00:14:30,640 --> 00:14:36,540
true, unpaid invoices. I had emails from Tom
Miller at HVAC and Dave Vance at Steele, dated

188
00:14:36,540 --> 00:14:41,760
three days after the pay application was submitted,
